questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Progressive and child-centered education &lt;/strong&gt;focuses on the child&amp;#39;s needs, abilities, interests, and learning styles. It emphasizes active learning and engagement, often through experiential, hands-on activities and democratic classroom environments that encourage student input and expression.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp;The use of digital technology and teaching-learning materials , learning from activities and experiences in a playful and exploratory manner, and the active participation of students with democratic and free expression are all components of this approach.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Emphasizing only course completion with a rigidly structured curriculum,&lt;/strong&gt; is &lt;strong&gt;not in line&lt;/strong&gt; with the principles of progressive, child-centered education.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;While structured curricula can be part of a balanced educational approach, an exclusive emphasis on completing a course or curriculum, often at the expense of fostering curiosity, creativity, and a love of learning, is contrary to the spirit of child-centered education.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus, it is concluded that &lt;strong&gt;option 3 is the correct answer.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Lev Vygotsky&lt;/span&gt;&amp;#39;, a Soviet psychologist, has propounded the &amp;quot;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Socio-cultural Theory&lt;/span&gt;&amp;quot;. This theory implies the idea that&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;social interaction&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;plays a crucial role in the development of learner&amp;#39;s cognitive ability.&amp;nbsp;Vygotsky has proposed the concept of&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;Zone of Proximal Development (ZPD)&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in his theory.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The concept of the Zone of proximal development&amp;nbsp;is widely used to &lt;strong&gt;study children&amp;#39;s mental development&lt;/strong&gt; as it relates to the educational context.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is a range of tasks too difficult for the child to do alone, but possible with the help of adults and more skilled peers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Zone of proximal development&amp;nbsp;concept is seen as a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;scaffolding&lt;/span&gt;, a structure of &amp;quot;support points&amp;quot; for performing an action.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It refers to the distance between the learner&amp;#39;s actual development level and his/her level of development under someone&amp;#39;s guidance.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;Hence it could be concluded that&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;Zone of Proximal Development (ZPD) means&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;the difference between what a child can do on their own, and what they can do with the help of a more knowledgeable other.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Theory of moral development&lt;/strong&gt;:&amp;nbsp;In early 1970, Lawrence Kohlberg became famous for his theory of moral development. The theory of moral development outlines a series of three Levels &amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;six developmental stages that children go through as they develop morality.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;Universal-Ethical-Principal Orientation:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;moral reasoning is based on abstract reasoning using universal ethical principles. Generally, the chosen principles are abstract rather than concrete and focus on ideas such as equality, dignity, or respect. Laws are valid only insofar as they are grounded in justice, and a commitment to justice carries with it an obligation to disobey unjust laws. People choose the ethical principles they want to follow, and if they violate those principles, they feel guilty. In this way, the individual acts because it is morally right to do so (and not because he or she wants to avoid punishment), it is in their best interest, it is expected, it is legal, or it is previously agreed upon.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Thus, &amp;lsquo;Right action is defined by self-chosen ethical principles of conscience&amp;rsquo; in Kolhberg&amp;rsquo;s stage of Universal Ethical principles.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;Kohlberg&amp;#39;s stages of moral development:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;table border=&quot;1&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;width:350px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Pre-con&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;ventional morality&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;It is the first stage of moral development and lasts until approximately age 9.&lt;/li&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;At the&amp;nbsp;pre-conventional level children don&amp;rsquo;t have a personal code of morality, and instead&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;moral decisions are shaped by the standards of adults&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;and the consequences of following or breaking their rules.&lt;/li&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;It is&amp;nbsp;on the&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;basis of existing social norms.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;For example&lt;/span&gt;, if an action leads to punishment it must be bad, and if it leads to a reward it must be good.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Conventional morality&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;It is the second stage of moral development and is characterized by an&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;acceptance of social rules concerning right and wrong.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;At the conventional level (most adolescents and adults), begin to internalize the moral standards of their adult role models.&lt;/li&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;Authority is internalized but not questioned, and reasoning is based on the norms of the group to which the person belongs.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Post-conventional m&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;orality&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;The third stage of moral development, and is characterized by an&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;individual&amp;rsquo;s understanding of universal ethical principles.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;These are abstract and ill-defined but might include: the preservation of life at all costs, and the importance of human dignity.&lt;/li&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;Individual judgment is based on self-chosen principles, and moral reasoning is based on individual rights and justice.&lt;/li&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;According to&amp;nbsp;Kohlberg&amp;nbsp;this level of moral reasoning is as far as most people get&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(0, 0, 0);&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Which of the following are the learning principles that explain how children learn ?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A. Children are reluctant to learn and hence teacher needs to motivate them.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;B. Children are naturally motivated to learn and capable of learning.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;C. Children learn in school hence every children must be sent to school.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;D. Children learn by making their own meaning and in a variety of ways.&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The learning principles that explain how children learn are:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Children are naturally motivated to learn and capable of learning. &lt;/strong&gt;This principle recognizes that children have an innate curiosity and drive to explore and learn about the world around them. They are naturally motivated to acquire knowledge and develop skills&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Children learn by making their own meaning in a variety of ways.&lt;/strong&gt; This principle emphasizes that children construct their understanding of concepts and ideas by actively engaging in learning. They make connections, ask questions, and apply their knowledge differently to make sense of the information they receive.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus, it is concluded that&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;B and D only is the correct answer.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Children that exhibit consistently exceptional success in educational endeavors are considered gifted. Within the highest two to three percent of the population, they have excellent intellectual capacity.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Your school boasts a diverse student body. Some children are brilliant, while others are artistic. As a teacher, the most important educational program for talented kids is to improve their thinking talents and allow them to participate in a variety of topics.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Talented pupils have a better understanding of the material than their peers their age. He has a startling degree of emotional depth and sensitivity for someone so young. My curiosity is high. Unusual topics and interests fascinate me.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A gifted child&amp;#39;s IQ will fall into one of the following categories: Mildly gifted people range from 115 to 130. Moderately gifted people are between the ages of 130 and 145. Those with an IQ of 145 to 160 are regarded as exceptionally gifted. Gifted and talented children require guidance and encouragement to maximize their abilities.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Encourage new and unique ways of thinking. Improving critical thinking necessitates doing informal tests of how things work. Teachers should foster gifted children&amp;#39;s critical thinking skills and offer them opportunities to participate in a range of activities.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;As a result, your school has a diverse range of students. Others youngsters are gifted, some are creative, and some are sluggish. As a teacher, the finest academic interventions for gifted students would be to develop their thinking abilities and provide them with the opportunity to participate in various concepts.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Allowing them to complete any work in the school and not sharing it with other pupils will not contribute to a positive school environment. Discrimination will be felt by pupils.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Motivating them to meet the minimum educational requirements and then providing them the same or another valuable object as a gift is never a good idea for their learning development.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&lt;span&gt;Right&amp;nbsp;to&amp;nbsp;Education&amp;nbsp;Act,&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&lt;span&gt;2009 ensures &amp;ldquo;Every child of age 6-14 years must be given free and compulsory&amp;nbsp;education&amp;rdquo;.&lt;/strong&lt;span&gt;&lt;/strong&lt;span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&lt;span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Right to&amp;nbsp;Education&amp;nbsp;Act&amp;nbsp;2009:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/strong&lt;span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;To provide free and compulsory&amp;nbsp;education&amp;nbsp;of all children in the age group of six&amp;nbsp;to&amp;nbsp;fourteen years as a Fundamental&amp;nbsp;Right&amp;nbsp;in such a manner as the State may, by law, determine.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;According&amp;nbsp;to&amp;nbsp;RTE&amp;nbsp;2009, the school should ensure the&amp;nbsp;Inclusion of Students&amp;nbsp;with disabilities/special needs as per the provision of the Act. &lt;strong&gt;(which means&amp;nbsp;inclusive&amp;nbsp;education).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Inclusion&amp;nbsp;requires&amp;nbsp;teachers&amp;nbsp;to accept the responsibility for creating schools in which all children can learn and feel they belong.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;The principles &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;of&amp;nbsp;Inclusive&amp;nbsp;education&amp;nbsp;in&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;cludes:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;No discrimination&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;among the students.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Equal&amp;nbsp;educational &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;opportunities&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;to all.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Adapting to the needs&amp;nbsp;of the students,&amp;nbsp;e.g., making institutions handicap-friendly.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Individual differences among the students are celebrated.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The student&amp;#39;s needs are taken seriously.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, the concept of Inclusive Education&amp;nbsp;as advocated in the Right to Education Act, 2009 is based on&amp;nbsp;a rights-based humanistic perspective.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Piaget in his &lt;strong&gt;theory of&amp;nbsp;cognitive development&lt;/strong&gt; describes changes in the thinking of a child at different stages of development. The child grows not only does her information increase but the manner in which she thinks also changes. At &lt;strong&gt;successive ages&lt;/strong&gt;, her thought is &lt;strong&gt;qualitatively different from the earlier ages&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;teacher&lt;/strong&gt; can play a&lt;strong&gt; vital role &lt;/strong&gt;to enable the student to make &lt;strong&gt;conceptual changes&lt;/strong&gt; in their thinking, he should-&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;make the child&amp;#39;s thinking &lt;strong&gt;progressive, cultured and civilized&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;by stimulating such methods which help in developing students&amp;#39; thinking process to analyses and integrate facts&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;help in&lt;strong&gt; developing their abilities &lt;/strong&gt;in the presentation of their ideas and facts clearly and fluently.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;a teacher should hear &lt;/strong&gt;the &lt;strong&gt;student&amp;#39;s point of view&lt;/strong&gt;, to get an &lt;strong&gt;explanation of her difficulties &lt;/strong&gt;and attitude towards her experience which help the child to make a conceptual change in their thinking.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;provide children opportunities for sharing of ideas &lt;/strong&gt;and&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;encourage discussion&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;categorizing, naming, and sporting activities&lt;span style=&quot;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;   letter-spacing: 0.8px;&quot;&gt;,&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;asking students to make connections and transfer activities&lt;/strong&gt; can also make&amp;nbsp;conceptual changes in a child&amp;#39;s thinking&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Here it is clear that to enable the student to make conceptual changes in their thinking, a teacher should&amp;nbsp;make clear and convincing explanations and have discussions with the students.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Individual differences&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;refer to distinctiveness and variations among people&amp;rsquo;s characteristics and behaviour patterns,&amp;nbsp;referring to the extent and kind of variations or similarities among people on some of the important psychological aspects such as intelligence, personality, interest, and aptitude.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;John Dewey,&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;an American philosopher has proposed the concept of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;Progressive&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Education&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;which emphasizes that&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;learning takes place only through &amp;#39;hands-on&amp;#39; approach&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;so the students must interact with their environment to adapt and learn.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Following are some advantages of individual difference in the progressive classroom-&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Understanding of individual differences&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;helps in planning course material and training programme.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Understanding of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;individual differences of the teachers&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;and the taught can&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;help in matching teaching and learning styles&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;for better- academic results.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To take care of individual differences you should&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;design&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;your&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;instructional activities to suit the mental level of each&amp;nbsp;student.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;the teacher&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;needs a system of instruction in which pace, a medium of presentation, study style, context and evaluation techniques are adapted to the needs of each individual.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The individual differences of students in a classroom are&amp;nbsp;advantageous as they lead the teacher to explore a wider pool of cognitive structures.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus from above-mentioned points, it is clear that &lt;strong&gt;individual differences in a progressive classroom should be treated as&amp;nbsp;important for planning of the teaching-learning process.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Assessment&lt;/strong&gt; is done to determine the&lt;strong&gt; outcomes&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;(what students have learned), &lt;strong&gt;process&lt;/strong&gt; (the way they learned), and their &lt;strong&gt;approach&lt;/strong&gt; to the learning before, during, or after the program or course.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;During instruction, the assessment can be used to determine what students are learning so that if there a need, the teacher can adjust their teacher.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is a&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;process-oriented approach&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;that is used to identify the areas for improvement in the learning process.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Formative assessment&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The purpose is to&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;diagnose the strength and weaknesses&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;of the students.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The results are used for&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;further improvement&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;of instruction and student&amp;#39;s better progress.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It refers to&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;continuous evaluation&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;by means of unit tests, assignments, etc.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is done&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;during the course&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;of instruction as it is focused on improving the achievements of learners.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It refers to the assessment of the instructional program which is still going on and can still be modified according to the learning requirements of learners.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Feedback&lt;/strong&gt; is provided to both the teachers and students.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Feedback to the teacher provides information for modifying instruction, developing the further learning program,&amp;nbsp;and helps in further individual remedial work.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Feedback to students provides reinforcement of successful learning and identifies the specific learning errors that need correction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
So, it is concluded that the formative assessment is typically conducted &lt;strong&gt;during&amp;nbsp;the development or improvement of a program.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/hint-text-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Hint&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The summative assessment&lt;strong&gt; measures the overall performance &lt;/strong&gt;of the students at the end of the course activity.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The purpose of this type of assessment is the&amp;nbsp;classification, comparison, and promotion&amp;nbsp;of the students.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Its results are used for&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;certification and passing judgment&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;on student&amp;#39;s achievements.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/confusion-points-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Confusion Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;table border=&quot;1&quot; cellpadding=&quot;0&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; style=&quot;width: 350px;&quot; width=&quot;500&quot;&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Formative evaluation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Summative evaluation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;The purpose is to&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;diagnose the strength and weaknesses&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;of the students.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;The purpose is to&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;classify and promotion&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;of students.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;It refers to&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;continuous evaluation&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;by means of unit tests, assignments, etc.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;It refers to&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;annual tests &lt;/strong&gt;and&lt;strong&gt; external&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;examinations.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;Its focus is to&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;improve&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;the student&amp;#39;s achievement.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;Its focus is to&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;measure&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;the student&amp;#39;s achievement.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;It&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;provides continuous feedback&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;to both teachers and students.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;It does&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;not provide feedback.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;It is done&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;during the course&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;of instruction.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;It is done at the&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;end of an academic course.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;gender stereotype&lt;/strong&gt; is a preconceived idea or a generalized belief about certain traits, characteristics, roles, or behaviors that are deemed appropriate for men and women based on their sex.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Addressing gender stereotypes effectively in a classroom setting requires an active effort to challenge and disrupt existing stereotypes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;One effective way to do this is by &lt;strong&gt;presenting examples that go against stereotypical notions about gender.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This might involve sharing stories or discussing individuals who don&amp;#39;t conform to traditional gender roles, thereby encouraging students to broaden their understanding of what different genders can do.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, we can conclude that in order to address gender stereotypes in the classroom, it is important to present examples that challenge those stereotypes.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
